      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Nobelium belongs to the actinides. It is a synthetic, radioactive metal - a transuranic element. All nobelium isotopes are radioactive; the most stable isotope is  </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">259</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">No, whose half-life is found to be 58 minutes. The following nobelium compounds are known: nobelium(II) oxide - NoO, nobelium(III) oxide – N</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">o</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">, nobelium(II) fluoride – No</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">F</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0"> and nobelium(III) fluoride – No</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">F</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. The element was first produced in 1957 by </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">a team of American, British and Swedish researchers, by the bombardment of curium-244 with carbon-12 ions. The element was named after Alfred Nobel - the inventor of dynamite and founder of the Nobel Prize.</text>
